div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D=
"ref1" data-has-spy=3D"true"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD1 =
mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong><span id=3D"ref3861=
35"></span>game theory</strong>,  branch of applied <a href=3D"https://www.=
britannica.com/science/mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">mathematics</a> that provides tools for analyzing situations in=
 which parties, called players, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic=
/decision-making" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">make d=
ecisions</a> that are interdependent. This interdependence causes each play=
er to consider the other player=E2=80=99s possible decisions, or strategies=
, in formulating <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/strategy-milit=
ary" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">strategy</a>. A sol=
ution to a game describes the optimal decisions of the players, who may hav=
e similar, opposed, or mixed interests, and the outcomes that may result fr=
om these decisions.</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_1_tablet" class=3D"adthr=
ive-ad  adthrive-content adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"><=
/div><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD=
2]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-par=
agraph">Although game theory can be and has been used to analyze parlour ga=
mes, its applications are much broader. In fact, game theory was originally=
 developed by the Hungarian-born American mathematician <span id=3D"ref3861=
37"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/John-von-Neumann=
" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">John von Neumann</a> a=
nd his <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Princeton-University" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">Princeton Univers=
ity</a> colleague <span id=3D"ref386138"></span><a href=3D"https://www.brit=
annica.com/money/Oskar-Morgenstern" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">Oskar Morgenstern</a>, a German-born American economist, to sol=
ve problems in <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/money/economics" class=
=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">economics</a>. In th=
eir book <em><span id=3D"ref386139"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannic=
a.com/topic/The-Theory-of-Games-and-Economic-Behavior" class=3D"md-crosslin=
k ">The Theory of Games and Economic Behavior</a></em> (1944), von Neumann =
and Morgenstern <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" dat=
a-term=3D"asserted" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/asserted"=
 data-type=3D"EB">asserted</a> that the mathematics developed for the physi=
cal sciences, which describes the workings of a disinterested nature, was a=
 poor model for economics. They observed that economics is much like a game=
, wherein players anticipate each other=E2=80=99s moves, and therefore requ=
ires a new kind of mathematics, which they called game theory. Game theory =
was further developed in the 1950s by American mathematician <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.britannica.com/biography/John-Nash" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-s=
how-preview=3D"true">John Nash</a>, who established the mathematical princi=
ples of game theory, a branch of mathematics that examines the rivalries be=
tween competitors with mixed interests.&nbsp;(The name for this branch of s=
tudies may be somewhat of a misnomer=E2=80=94game theory generally does not=
 share the fun or frivolity associated with games.)</p><!--[MOD2]--><span c=
lass=3D"marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD3]--><span class=3D"marke=
r PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><em><a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.britannica.com/topic/rationality" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-sh=
ow-preview=3D"true">(Read Steven Pinker=E2=80=99s Britannica entry on ratio=
nality.)</a></em></p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthriv=
e-ad  adthrive-content adthrive-content-2" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></d=
iv><!--[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD4]=
--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-parag=
raph">Game theory has been applied to a wide variety of situations in which=
 the choices of players interact to affect the outcome. In stressing the st=
rategic aspects of <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/decision-mak=
ing" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">decision m=
aking</a>, or aspects controlled by the players rather than by pure chance,=
 the theory both <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" da=
ta-term=3D"supplements" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/suppl=
ements" data-type=3D"EB">supplements</a> and goes beyond the classical theo=
ry of <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/probability-theory" cla=
ss=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">probability</a>. It has bee=
n used, for example, to determine what political coalitions or business con=
glomerates are likely to form, the optimal price at which to sell products =
or services in the face of competition, the power of a voter or a bloc of v=
oters, whom to select for a jury, the best site for a manufacturing plant, =
and the behaviour of certain animals and plants in their struggle for survi=
val. It has even been used to challenge the legality of certain voting syst=
ems.</p><!--[MOD4]--><span class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span><!--[PRE=
MOD5]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-=
paragraph">It would be surprising if any one theory could address such an e=
normous range of =E2=80=9Cgames,=E2=80=9D and in fact there is no single ga=
me theory. A number of theories have been proposed, each applicable to diff=
erent situations and each with its own concepts of what <a class=3D"md-dict=
ionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"constitutes" href=3D"http=
s://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/constitutes" data-type=3D"MW">consti=
tutes</a> a solution. This article describes some simple games, discusses d=
ifferent theories, and outlines principles underlying game theory. Addition=
al concepts and methods that can be used to analyze and solve decision prob=
lems are treated in the article <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/scien=
ce/optimization" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">optimiz=
ation</a>.</p><!--[MOD5]--><span class=3D"marker MOD5 mod-inline"></span></=
section>           <!--[H2]--><span class=3D"marker h2"></span><div class=
=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D"ref22612=
" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h1">Classification of games</h2> <!--=
[PREMOD6]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD6 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"to=
pic-paragraph">Games can be classified according to certain significant fea=
tures, the most obvious of which is the number of players. Thus, a game can=
 be designated as being a one-person, two-person, or <em>n</em>-person (wit=
h <em>n</em> greater than two) game, with games in each category having the=
ir own distinctive features. In addition, a player need not be an individua=
l; it may be a nation, a corporation, or a team <a class=3D"md-dictionary-l=
ink md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"comprising" href=3D"https://www.m=
erriam-webster.com/dictionary/comprising" data-type=3D"MW">comprising</a> m=
any people with shared interests.</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_3_tablet" =
class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-content adthrive-content-3" style=3D"min-hei=
ght: 250px;"></div><!--[MOD6]--><span class=3D"marker MOD6 mod-inline"></sp=
an> <!--[PREMOD7]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD7 mod-inline"></span><p cla=
ss=3D"topic-paragraph">In games of perfect information, such as <span id=3D=
"ref386140"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/chess" class=
=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">chess</a>, each player knows =
everything about the game at all times. <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.c=
om/topic/poker-card-game" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true=
">Poker</a>, on the other hand, is an example of a game of imperfect inform=
ation because players do not know all of their opponents=E2=80=99 cards.</p=
><div class=3D"module-spacing">
