</div></div><!--[MOD7]--><span class=3D"marker MOD7 mod-inline"></span> <!-=
-[PREMOD8]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD8 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"t=
opic-paragraph">The extent to which the goals of the players coincide or co=
nflict is another basis for classifying games. <span id=3D"ref386148"></spa=
n><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/constant-sum-game" class=3D"m=
d-crosslink ">Constant-sum games</a> are games of total conflict, which are=
 also called games of pure competition. Poker, for example, is a constant-s=
um game because the combined wealth of the players remains constant, though=
 its distribution shifts in the course of play.</p><!--[MOD8]--><span class=
=3D"marker MOD8 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD9]--><span class=3D"marker P=
REMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Players in constant-=
sum games have completely opposed interests, whereas in <span id=3D"ref8918=
91"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/variable-sum-game" c=
lass=3D"md-crosslink ">variable-sum games</a> they may all be winners or lo=
sers. In a labour-management <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-t=
t-off eb" data-term=3D"dispute" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictiona=
ry/dispute" data-type=3D"EB">dispute</a>, for example, the two parties cert=
ainly have some conflicting interests, but both will benefit if a strike is=
 averted.</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_4_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  ad=
thrive-content adthrive-content-4" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><!--[=
MOD9]--><span class=3D"marker MOD9 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD10]--><sp=
an class=3D"marker PREMOD10 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"=
>Variable-sum games can be further distinguished as being either <span id=
=3D"ref386163"></span>cooperative or <span id=3D"ref386164"></span>noncoope=
rative. In <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/cooperative" class=
=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">cooperative</a> game=
s players can communicate and, most important, make binding agreements; in =
noncooperative games players may communicate, but they cannot make binding =
agreements, such as an enforceable contract. An automobile salesperson and =
a potential customer will be engaged in a cooperative game if they agree on=
 a price <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/ampersand" class=3D"md=
-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">and sign</a> a contract. H=
owever, the dickering that they do to reach this point will be noncooperati=
ve. Similarly, when people bid independently at an <a href=3D"https://www.b=
ritannica.com/money/auction" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-pre=
view=3D"true">auction</a> they are playing a noncooperative game, even thou=
gh the high bidder agrees to complete the purchase.</p><!--[MOD10]--><span =
class=3D"marker MOD10 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD11]--><span class=3D"m=
arker PREMOD11 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Finally, a g=
ame is said to be <span id=3D"ref386143"></span>finite when each player has=
 a <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"fin=
ite" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/finite" data-type=3D"EB"=
>finite</a> number of options, the number of players is finite, and the gam=
e cannot go on indefinitely. Chess, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/t=
opic/checkers" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">checkers<=
/a>, <span id=3D"ref386144"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/to=
pic/poker-card-game" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">pok=
er</a>, and most parlour games are finite. <span id=3D"ref386145"></span>In=
finite games are more subtle and will only be touched upon in this article.=
</p><!--[MOD11]--><span class=3D"marker MOD11 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREM=
OD12]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD12 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic=
-paragraph">A game can be described in one of three ways: in extensive, nor=
mal, or characteristic-function form. (Sometimes these forms are combined, =
as described in the section <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/g=
ame-theory/The-prisoners-dilemma#ref255880" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-sh=
ow-preview=3D"true">Theory of moves</a>.) Most parlour games, which progres=
s step by step, one move at a time, can be modeled as games in extensive fo=
rm. Extensive-form games can be described by a =E2=80=9Cgame tree,=E2=80=9D=
 in which each turn is a <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-of=
f eb" data-term=3D"vertex" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/ve=
rtex" data-type=3D"EB">vertex</a> of the tree, with each branch indicating =
the players=E2=80=99 successive choices.</p><!--[MOD12]--><span class=3D"ma=
rker MOD12 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD13]--><span class=3D"marker PREMO=
D13 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The normal (strategic) =
form is primarily used to describe two-person games. In this form a game is=
 represented by a payoff <span id=3D"ref386146"></span>matrix, wherein each=
 row describes the strategy of one player and each column describes the str=
ategy of the other player. The <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/scienc=
e/matrix-mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D=
"true">matrix</a> entry at the intersection of each row and column gives th=
e outcome of each player choosing the corresponding strategy. The payoffs t=
o each player associated with this outcome are the basis for determining wh=
ether the strategies are =E2=80=9Cin equilibrium,=E2=80=9D or stable.</p><!=
--[MOD13]--><span class=3D"marker MOD13 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD14]-=
-><span class=3D"marker PREMOD14 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-parag=
raph">The characteristic-function form is generally used to analyze games w=
ith more than two players. It indicates the minimum <a class=3D"md-dictiona=
ry-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"value" href=3D"https://www.br=
itannica.com/dictionary/value" data-type=3D"EB">value</a> that each coaliti=
on of players=E2=80=94including single-player coalitions=E2=80=94can guaran=
tee for itself when playing against a coalition made up of all the other pl=
ayers.</p><div class=3D"js-qf-module qf-module px-40 px-sm-20 py-15 mx-auto=
 module-spacing font-14 bg-gray-50 rounded">

