s=3D"h1">One-person games</h2> <!--[PREMOD15]--><span class=3D"marker PREMO=
D15 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">One-person games are al=
so known as games against nature. With no opponents, the player only needs =
to list available options and then choose the optimal outcome. When chance =
is involved the game might seem to be more complicated, but in principle th=
e decision is still relatively simple. For example, a person deciding wheth=
er to carry an umbrella weighs the costs and benefits of carrying or not ca=
rrying it. While this person may make the wrong decision, there does not ex=
ist a conscious opponent. That is, nature is presumed to be completely indi=
fferent to the player=E2=80=99s decision, and the person can base his decis=
ion on simple probabilities. One-person games hold little interest for game=
 theorists.</p><!--[MOD15]--><span class=3D"marker MOD15 mod-inline"></span=
