=3D"true"> <h1 class=3D"h1">Two-person constant-sum games</h1><!--[TOC]--> =
<div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"2" id=
=3D"ref22615" data-has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h2">Games of <span id=3D"=
ref1084980"></span>perfect information</h2> <!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=3D"=
marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The simplest=
 game of any real <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" d=
ata-term=3D"theoretical" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/theo=
retical" data-type=3D"EB">theoretical</a> interest is a two-person constant=
-sum game of perfect information. Examples of such games include <a href=3D=
"https://www.britannica.com/topic/chess" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " d=
ata-show-preview=3D"true">chess</a>, checkers, and the Japanese game of <a =
href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/go-game" class=3D"md-crosslink " d=
ata-show-preview=3D"true">go</a>. In 1912 the German mathematician Ernst Ze=
rmelo proved that such games are strictly determined; by making use of all =
available information, the players can deduce strategies that are <span id=
=3D"ref386150"></span>optimal, which makes the outcome preordained (strictl=
y determined). In chess, for example, exactly one of three outcomes must oc=
cur if the players make optimal choices: (1) White wins (has a strategy tha=
t wins against any strategy of Black); (2) Black wins; or (3) White and Bla=
ck draw. In principle, a sufficiently powerful <a href=3D"https://www.brita=
nnica.com/technology/supercomputer" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">supercomputer</a> could determine which of the three outcomes w=
ill occur. However, considering that there are some 10<sup>43</sup> distinc=
t 40-move games of chess possible, there seems no possibility that such a c=
omputer will be developed now or in the foreseeable future. Therefore, whil=
e chess is of only minor interest in game theory, it is likely to remain a =
game of enduring <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" da=
ta-term=3D"intellectual" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary=
/intellectual" data-type=3D"MW">intellectual</a> interest.</p><!--[MOD1]-->=
<span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span> </section> <div class=3D"md-=
sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"2" id=3D"ref22616" data-=
has-spy=3D"true"> <h2 class=3D"h2">Games of <span id=3D"ref1084981"></span>=
imperfect information</h2> <!--[PREMOD2]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD2 mo=
d-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">A =E2=80=9C<span id=3D"ref386=
153"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/saddlepoint" clas=
s=3D"md-crosslink ">saddlepoint</a>=E2=80=9D in a two-person constant-sum g=
ame is the outcome that rational players would choose. (Its name derives fr=
om its being the minimum of a row that is also the maximum of a column in a=
 payoff matrix=E2=80=94to be illustrated shortly=E2=80=94which corresponds =
to the shape of a saddle.) A saddlepoint always exists in games of perfect =
information but may or may not exist in games of imperfect information. By =
choosing a <span id=3D"ref386152"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.=
com/topic/strategy-military" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"t=
rue">strategy</a> associated with this outcome, each player obtains an amou=
nt at least equal to his payoff at that outcome, no matter what the other p=
layer does. This payoff is called the value of the game; as in perfect-info=
rmation games, it is preordained by the players=E2=80=99 choices of strateg=
ies associated with the saddlepoint, making such games strictly determined.=
</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class=3D"marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD=
3]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><div class=3D"assembl=
