game in <span class=3D"link-blue media-overlay-link asmref" data-href=3D"/m=
edia/1/224893/85150">Table 1</span> is used to illustrate the calculation o=
f a saddlepoint. Two political parties, <em>A</em> and <em>B</em>, must eac=
h decide how to handle a controversial issue in a certain election. Each pa=
rty can either support the issue, oppose it, or evade it by being <a class=
=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"ambiguous" hre=
f=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ambiguous" data-type=3D"MW"=
>ambiguous</a>. The decisions by <em>A</em> and <em>B</em> on this issue de=
termine the percentage of the vote that each party receives. The entries in=
 the payoff <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/matrix-mathematic=
s" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">matrix</a> r=
epresent party <em>A</em>=E2=80=99s percentage of the vote (the remaining p=
ercentage goes to <em>B</em>). When, for example, <em>A</em> supports the i=
ssue and <em>B</em> evades it, <em>A</em> gets 80 percent and <em>B</em> 20=
 percent of the vote.</p><!--[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline=
"></span> <!--[PREMOD4]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span>=
<p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Assume that each party wants to maximize its v=
ote. <em>A</em>=E2=80=99s decision seems difficult at first because it depe=
nds on <em>B</em>=E2=80=99s choice of strategy. <em>A</em> does best to sup=
port if <em>B</em> evades, oppose if <em>B</em> supports, and evade if <em>=
B</em> opposes. <em>A</em> must therefore consider <em>B</em>=E2=80=99s dec=
ision before making its own. Note that no matter what <em>A</em> does, <em>=
B</em> obtains the largest percentage of the vote (smallest percentage for =
<em>A</em>) by opposing the issue rather than supporting it or evading it. =
Once <em>A</em> recognizes this, its strategy obviously should be to evade,=
 settling for 30 percent of the vote. Thus, a 30 to 70 percent division of =
the vote, to <em>A</em> and <em>B</em> respectively, is the game=E2=80=99s =
saddlepoint.</p><!--[MOD4]--><span class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span>=
 <!--[PREMOD5]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p class=
=3D"topic-paragraph">A more <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt=
-off eb" data-term=3D"systematic" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictio=
nary/systematic" data-type=3D"EB">systematic</a> way of finding a saddlepoi=
nt is to determine the so-called <span id=3D"ref386154"></span>maximin and =
<span id=3D"ref386155"></span>minimax values. <em>A</em> first determines t=
he <span id=3D"ref386156"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/scie=
nce/minimum" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">minimum</a>=
 percentage of votes it can obtain for each of its strategies; it then find=
s the <span id=3D"ref386157"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/s=
cience/maximum" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">maximum<=
/a> of these three minimum values, giving the maximin. The minimum percenta=
ges <em>A</em> will get if it supports, opposes, or evades are, respectivel=
y, 20, 25, and 30. The largest of these, 30, is the maximin value. Similarl=
y, for each strategy <em>B</em> chooses, it determines the maximum percenta=
ge of votes <em>A</em> will win (and thus the minimum that it can win). In =
this case, if <em>B</em> supports, opposes, or evades, the maximum <em>A</e=
m> will get is 80, 30, and 80, respectively. <em>B</em> will obtain its lar=
gest percentage by minimizing <em>A</em>=E2=80=99s maximum percent of the v=
ote, giving the minimax. The smallest of <em>A</em>=E2=80=99s maximum <a cl=
ass=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"values" hre=
f=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/values" data-type=3D"EB">values<=
/a> is 30, so 30 is <em>B</em>=E2=80=99s minimax value. Because both the mi=
