hing; when they go to different safes, the safecracker gets the contents of=
 the unprotected safe.</p><!--[MOD7]--><span class=3D"marker MOD7 mod-inlin=
e"></span> <!--[PREMOD8]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD8 mod-inline"></span=
><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">In such a game, game theory does not indicate=
 that any one particular strategy is best. Instead, it prescribes that a st=
rategy be chosen in accordance with a <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com=
/science/distribution-function" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-=
preview=3D"true">probability distribution</a>, which in this simple example=
 is quite easy to calculate. In larger and more complex games, finding this=
 strategy involves solving a problem in <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.c=
om/science/linear-programming-mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">linear programming</a>, which can be considerab=
ly more difficult.</p><!--[MOD8]--><span class=3D"marker MOD8 mod-inline"><=
/span> <!--[PREMOD9]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p =
class=3D"topic-paragraph">To calculate the <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link m=
d-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"appropriate" href=3D"https://www.brita=
nnica.com/dictionary/appropriate" data-type=3D"EB">appropriate</a> probabil=
ity distribution in this example, each player adopts a strategy that makes =
him indifferent to what his opponent does. Assume that the guard protects <=
em>S</em>1 with probability <em>p</em> and <em>S</em>2 with probability 1 =
=E2=88=92 <em>p</em>. Thus, if the safecracker tries <em>S</em>1, he will b=
e successful whenever the guard protects <em>S</em>2. In other words, he wi=
ll get $10,000 with probability 1 =E2=88=92 <em>p</em> and $0 with probabil=
ity <em>p</em> for an average gain of $10,000(1 =E2=88=92 <em>p</em>). Simi=
larly, if the safecracker tries <em>S</em>2, he will get $100,000 with prob=
ability <em>p</em> and $0 with probability 1 =E2=88=92 <em>p</em> for an av=
erage gain of $100,000<em>p</em>.</p><!--[MOD9]--><span class=3D"marker MOD=
9 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD10]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD10 mod-i=
nline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">The guard will be <a class=3D"md=
-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"indifferent" href=3D=
"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/indifferent" data-type=3D"EB">indiff=
erent</a> to which safe the safecracker chooses if the average amount stole=
n is the same in both cases=E2=80=94that is, if $10,000(1 =E2=88=92 <em>p</=
em>) =3D $100,000<em>p</em>. Solving for <em>p</em> gives <em>p</em> =3D 1/=
11. If the guard protects <em>S</em>1 with probability 1/11 and <em>S</em>2=
 with probability 10/11, he will lose, on average, no more than about $9,09=
1 whatever the safecracker does.</p><!--[MOD10]--><span class=3D"marker MOD=
10 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD11]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD11 mod-=
inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Using the same kind of argument=
